Comment:
The Gray Man is based on the first of 11 books, which I all highly recommend reading or listening to on Audible. The author, Mark Greaney, also co-authored books with Tom Clancy and Rip Rawlings. He literally finished the last 3 Tom Clancy novels after Tom Clancy's death and wrote 4 more Tom Clancy based books. However, The Gray Man series of books is rather different from the typical Tom Clancy spy novels. They are more action-packed and violent.

The first book, which this movie is based on, is better. They changed quite a few details for the movie. If you are interested in reading the books, start with the 1st. The first book came out in 2009 and had a movie option within 3 months. It influenced a lot of other books, movies and TV shows.

author: @revolzyy

Comment: ¬†@revolzyy¬† In order for certain movies to be a candidate for a specific award ceremony they need to be released in a minimum number of theaters by a specific date. As long as the movie is initially released to these theaters by a specific date they can participate in a particular awards season. "The Deer Hunter" was given a small release in December 1978, and used the oscar nominations to fuel ticket sales for a February 1979 wide release. Netflix is using this trick to get nominations, and hence more industry credibility, except they never give the movie a wide release in theaters.

Comment:
This movie is based on the first of 11 books, which I highly recommend reading. The author, Mark Greaney, also co-authored books with Tom Clancy and Rip Rawlings. He literally finished the last 3 Tom Clancy novels after Tom Clancy's death and wrote 4 more Tom Clancy based books. However, The Gray Man series of books is rather different from the typical Tom Clancy spy novels. They are more action-packed, violent and political. They are about a former CIA operator, Courtland Gentry, that became an assassin for hire after the CIA tried to assassinate him. The first book came out in 2009 and influenced a number of other writers. The books are a mix between fiction and the real world. In the real world, shit happens, so does in the books.

This movie butchered the first book to the point that they may have broken the story line so badly that there won't be another Gray Man movie or series. They completely changed the reason why the CIA is after Court Gentry, thus eliminated an entire book that explains it. They completely changed the Goon Squad (GS with Sierra 1-6) story too, as Sierra Six was not primarily a singleton operator. Instead, Violator (Gentry before the Goon Squad) was. They completely changed who Sir Donald Fitzroy is, a Brit with 30 years of MI-5 experience, and killed him off, thus eliminating another entire book  Gosling looks too clean and wears too flashy clothes for the Gray Man. Ironically, Chris Evans was, I think, the right cast for Floyd. Oh, Loyd. Yes, they missed that whole word play that Gentry did with Loyd's name too.

Comment: I think its high time for the Indian or Asian audience who are going to watch the movie for Dhanush only to ignore the movie altogether. Netflix's aim to capture the Indian market by giving inconsequential roles in hollywood films to Indian actors is quite smart but we aren't dumb here. I am not asking to significantly increase their screen time unnecessarily but to gives them parts that make a difference to the movie and serve some purpose. But these days it feels like that they are casted just to fill in a space of cast they need an Asian actor/actress for. I think Indian actors are capable enough to hone their skills and show their talent in Indian films and make them matketable enough to be distributed worldwide. They have enough caliber as any other hollywood actor. And hollywood films are not the only way to explore the western market. But try n make something that western audiences and people around the world will be wishing to buy. And venture into world markets just as hollywood does. This is how these hollywood people will understand that Asian talent is not just to support them in their films but to lead. I hope this puts a sense of critical thinking in all the Asians and especially Indians. Much love..!!

Comment:
The movie writers royally screwed this one up. They made several tactical errors that will come back to harm them in their pocket for any follow-on movies. Keep on reading! I read them all and it just gets better and better. The books also go back in time, explaining a lot of context.

By the way, the first book came out in 2009, way before John Wick was made. I am sure it influenced John Wick. The movie option was purchased something like 2 months after the book came out in 2009. It took them until now to actually produce it.

Read though the entire Gray Man series (11 books). Then read though Jack Carr's Terminal List series (5 books). Then go back to Mark Greaney and read "Armored" (1 book). Then start with Brian Andrews' and Jeffrey Wilson's Tier One Thrillers (6 books) and Sons of Valor series (2 books). After reading those 25 books, there will be a new book for the Gray Man, Terminal List and  Sons of Valor to read.
